<div id="review_2954533864" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2954533864" />
    <a title="Melissa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9796511-melissa"><img alt="Melissa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509110434p2/9796511.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2954533864?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melissa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melissa" href="/user/show/9796511-melissa">Melissa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Melissa by: </span>
      Goodreads
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9796511-melissa?shelf=algeria">algeria</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2954533864" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11280106510427571944">This is a heart-felt memoir of a Muslim woman’s struggle to reconcile her love of her country with her embrace of Western-style liberty. Djebar is fortunate as a girl in mid-century Algeria to be allowed to continue in the colonial school system even as her cousins and friends drop out to assume the traditional full-faced veil and be cloistered in their homes. But the more she advances in her education and independence, the farther she grows from the women of her community. The French language, </span>
  <span id="freeText11280106510427571944" style="display:none">This is a heart-felt memoir of a Muslim woman’s struggle to reconcile her love of her country with her embrace of Western-style liberty. Djebar is fortunate as a girl in mid-century Algeria to be allowed to continue in the colonial school system even as her cousins and friends drop out to assume the traditional full-faced veil and be cloistered in their homes. But the more she advances in her education and independence, the farther she grows from the women of her community. The French language, the language of her people’s oppressors, ironically becomes the language of her liberation as well as a symbol of the distance between her and her people.<br /><br />There’s a lot to unpack in this brilliant work. I loved the emphasis on the Algerian woman’s experience and perspective and on giving women voices who have traditionally been silenced. There’s the dichotomy of women displaying strength and bravery against the colonial system and yet still oppressed by their own society’s norms. Most of all, I appreciated entering into a completely different perspectives and experiences.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11280106510427571944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


