    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3211411897" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3211411897" />
    <a title="Thomas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52482799-thomas"><img alt="Thomas" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3211411897?book_show_action=true">Mar 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas" href="/user/show/52482799-thomas">Thomas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3211411897" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17584768147176436521">Fantasia is an dense, ambitious and beautiful conceptual novel, very different and refreshing in its style and structure. It is part autobiography and part historical novel but at its heart Fantasia is a novel about Algerian women and their lost voices. The recovery of repressed stories is at the core of much postcolonial literature; Assia Djebar does it better than most, partly because she bares her teeth and her intent and sets out to openly and bravely confront exactly this silence, to uneart</span>
  <span id="freeText17584768147176436521" style="display:none">Fantasia is an dense, ambitious and beautiful conceptual novel, very different and refreshing in its style and structure. It is part autobiography and part historical novel but at its heart Fantasia is a novel about Algerian women and their lost voices. The recovery of repressed stories is at the core of much postcolonial literature; Assia Djebar does it better than most, partly because she bares her teeth and her intent and sets out to openly and bravely confront exactly this silence, to unearth it, to give those voices identities and to tie those stories together into the voice of her own, disjointed autobiography. Initially Fantasia alternates neatly between historical chapters about the Algerian war with France in the 1830s and chapters narrated in the first person in the 1960s - a young Algerian girl, her upbringing and her education, presumably Djebar herself. This structure loosens and fractures in the second half of the book, taking on a more flowing, lyrical quality (set to musical movements) and telling numerous stories from the Algerian war of independence in the 1950s, each from the point of view of another female character.<br /><br />This springing between stories and points of view, as well as periods in recent Algerian history makes Fantasia quite a difficult novel to read. You have to quickly adjust to each new voice. In some some chapters Djebar seems to flit between first and third person narrators at will. That said, the book never feels disjointed. There is an easy cohesion brought about by Djebar's direct style and thematical bullishness. Importantly, every story told is captivating in its own right. Fantastia never feels dull or overly difficult. There is so much linking the voices together - the struggles of their gender, the female body, love, the men in their lives, language, a relationship with "France" and all that entails, ritual and culture, and a deep rooted, buried sense of sensuality - that the novel always seems to be a single work, never a collection of short stories or an episodic autobiography. The lines between fiction (authorial license) and historical events is vague, justly so, and it works well together to give an epic sense of the Algerian story, a history of wars, resistance and world culture.<br /><br />One of the central themes in Djebar's novel is the difference between written and oral accounts of history. She tells of the war with France mainly through the eyes (and written words) of French war correspondants; soldiers, officers, a painter, travellers. These documented accounts should have a indisputable quality about them but Djebar makes sure that the oral accounts that make up the chorus of Algerian women telling the story of independence have an equal resonance. They merge so smoothly with her own accounts and with each other, creating an almost universal voice of female suffering and struggle. Each of those struggles are reflected in Djebar's own words and commentaries. The strength of this resistance is the strength of the book, whether it be physical (the story of a young rebel tortured by the French) or through language (Djebar's own treatise on women who "raise their voices" for example). Djebar knows exactly what she wants to say and has the eloquence and tenacity to get it across in this impressive, complex form.<br /><br />There are many memorable scenes which transform this book of ideas into a truly dramatical narrative as well - the battle for Algiers and the destruction of the great fortress by the French artillery, the woman whose farm is repeatedly burned down, the women stripped of their jewels after a great betrayal outside the city of Miliana. One stands out above the rest - the rebels smoked out of their cave hideouts during the war of independence. These scenes of violence and injustice steer Fantasia away from being a book solely about the silencing and the repossession of the Berber-Arabic/Algerian woman's voice. It is also a book about Algeria as a historical entity and its violent relationship with France and the French language. Furthermore, Djebar's book of resistence is one of the best novelistic representations of the struggle for post-colonial identity that I have read. Many of the themes here are universal, unfortunately, and represent a greater struggle in Africa and beyond.<br /><br />Read alone as a historical representation, or delved into as a fascinating and vitriolic book of identity, or even as a cultural and social portrait of Algeria, its sense of family, its relationship with religion, and the tapestry of its linguistic herritage, Fantastia is a many faceted, difficult and deep novel that could be read from many angles. Assia Djebar's lyricism and bravery links the disparate parts and intentions together to form a cohesive, powerful piece of post-colonial reconstruction, a salvaging of lost voices from the shipwreck of centuries of violence. 8</span>
  <a data-text-id="17584768147176436521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


