  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2468217723" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2468217723" />
    <a title="Nikhil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11619849-nikhil"><img alt="Nikhil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1344276050p2/11619849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2468217723?book_show_action=true">Jul 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nikhil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nikhil" href="/user/show/11619849-nikhil">Nikhil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780435086213" href="/book/show/457864.Fantasia">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11619849-nikhil?shelf=african">african</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11619849-nikhil?shelf=middle-eastern">middle-eastern</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11619849-nikhil?shelf=poco">poco</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2468217723" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3541943831753717505">This book is very well written and crushingly literary. Djebar is clearly brilliant. I will certainly need to revisit this text to get more out from it. Broadly, the text juxtaposes the violence of Algerian colonization, both physical and intellectual, with the violence of the harem. <br/><br/>A great deal of the text has to do with the tension between native and colonizers language, and what it means to be a person straddling both. Is all knowledge written in French, even if written by a post Colonial Al</span>
  <span id="freeText3541943831753717505" style="display:none">This book is very well written and crushingly literary. Djebar is clearly brilliant. I will certainly need to revisit this text to get more out from it. Broadly, the text juxtaposes the violence of Algerian colonization, both physical and intellectual, with the violence of the harem. <br /><br />A great deal of the text has to do with the tension between native and colonizers language, and what it means to be a person straddling both. Is all knowledge written in French, even if written by a post Colonial Algerian subject, merely recreating colonial knowledge by adhering to colonial forms? By adhering to the form, style, phrasing, and structure of the colonial language is the content inherently then colonial? Djebar and Ngugi would say yes, as would the many postcolonial literary movement to that advocated a return to writing in the Native tongue. These movements, however, seem to miss the fact that the colonizers language by living in the colony and mutating can become a Native language as well: English seems to reflect this more, as unlike French, it is less concerned with prioritizing a static form. Related to this discussion is the notion of a separated self, with different parts of your life lived in different languages, and the subject unable to map the two languages into the opposite sphere. The text would posit that separation as a recreation of the Manichaean physical colonial world within the self. <br /><br />Somehow Djebar manages to do the impossible: construct a valid way of using the land as Woman metaphor without resorting to insulting nonsense like invasions as metaphoric rape (in the text, rape is rape). Largely this is done by grounding the text in the voices, stories, and traditions of Algerian women, and juxtaposing these storytellings with the writings of men, French or Algerian. <br /><br />The Fantasia she wishes dead, that Djebar celebrates the death knell of, is ultimately a product of both the colonial violence that has kept Algeria in states of violence for nearly 200 years, and the masculinity that prioritizes honor in the form of dead or brutalized women and tradition over a reading of Islam grounded in love. Ultimately, Djebar’s celebration is premature: a decade after the publication of this text, Algeria erupted into war again, and the Fantasia returned. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3541943831753717505" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


