  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3818056313" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3818056313" />
    <a title="Joel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9058325-joel"><img alt="Joel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1335396222p2/9058325.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3818056313?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joel" href="/user/show/9058325-joel">Joel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9058325-joel?shelf=middle-east">middle-east</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9058325-joel?shelf=africa">africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9058325-joel?shelf=neustadt-prize">neustadt-prize</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9058325-joel?shelf=world-lit">world-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3818056313" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16708852778362084069">A book by an Algerian writer, which alternates autobiographical chapters (at least I think they’re autobiographical; I can’t swear to that, though) with chapters about Algerian history. I wouldn’t say that the two types of chapters coexist easily.<br/><br/>In the first half of the book, the historical chapters focus on the French invasion of Algeria in 1830 and attempted uprisings over the next couple decades. Djebar tells us something about the various people- primarily French officers- who left firsthan</span>
  <span id="freeText16708852778362084069" style="display:none">A book by an Algerian writer, which alternates autobiographical chapters (at least I think they’re autobiographical; I can’t swear to that, though) with chapters about Algerian history. I wouldn’t say that the two types of chapters coexist easily.<br /><br />In the first half of the book, the historical chapters focus on the French invasion of Algeria in 1830 and attempted uprisings over the next couple decades. Djebar tells us something about the various people- primarily French officers- who left firsthand accounts of these events, and speculates about what they may have left out. The second half of the book concerns the Algerian independence struggle of the 1950s; these chapters are more like an oral history, presenting the stories of women who Djebar interviewed personally.<br /><br />Djebar’s themes are colonialism, the way her society treats women, and language. As she recounts in her autobiographical sections, her father’s desire to see her educated meant that she didn’t grow up cloistered away from the world like the rest of her female relatives; but she’s frustrated, as an adult writer, by the fact that this education has left her more comfortable writing in French- the language of the colonizer- than in her own native language.<br /><br />This would be an easier book to like if it weren’t full- particularly in the autobiographical sections- of passages like this:<br /><br /><i>“Voiceless, cut off from my mother’s words by some trick of memory, I managed to pass through the dark waters of the corridor, miraculously inviolate, not even guessing at the enclosing walls. The shock of the first words blurted out: the truth emerging from a break in my stammering voice. From what nocturnal reef of pleasure did I manage to wrest this truth?”</i><br /><br />Even in context, that’s a rather opaque paragraph. The book is flecked with such passages; vague, allusive, elliptical, elusive. It’s a book which has a lot of things to say which are worth reading; but if you’re prone to headaches, this is the sort of writing that might well give you one.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16708852778362084069" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

